      "content": """# Professional Exposure Control

## Beyond Technical Correctness

Professional photography uses exposure creatively, not just technically. Learn to control mood and impact through deliberate exposure choices.

### Intentional Overexposure (High-Key)
• Creates bright, airy mood (+1 to +2 stops)
• Flatters skin tones in portraits
• Popular for lifestyle and beauty photography
• Requires careful highlight preservation

### Intentional Underexposure (Low-Key)
• Dramatic, moody atmosphere (-1 to +2 stops)
• Emphasizes form and texture
• Common in luxury and editorial work
• Preserve shadow detail where needed

### Zone System Basics
Ansel Adams' system divides tones into 11 zones (0-X):
• Zone V: Middle gray (meter reading)
• Zone III: Textured shadows
• Zone VII: Textured highlights
Place key subjects in appropriate zones for desired effect.

### Practical Application
1. Identify key subject tone
2. Determine desired zone placement
3. Meter and adjust exposure
4. Verify with histogram
5. Refine as needed

### Scene-Specific Strategies
**Portraits:** Skin typically Zone IV-VI
**Landscapes:** Balance sky and foreground (2-3 stop difference)
**Products:** Control background separately from subject

Master creative exposure to serve your artistic vision, not camera automation.""",
