      "content": """# Focus Stacking Mastery

## What is Focus Stacking?

Taking multiple photos at different focus distances, then blending in post to create extended depth of field impossible in a single shot.

### Why Stack Focus?
• Overcome depth of field limitations
• Use optimal aperture (avoid diffraction)
• Commercial detail requirements
• Macro photography necessity

### Essential Setup
**Required:**
• Sturdy tripod (critical)
• Manual focus control
• Consistent lighting
• Focus stacking software

**Recommended:**
• Macro rail for precise movement
• Remote shutter release
• Camera with focus bracketing

### Shooting Technique

**Camera Settings:**
• Manual mode
• Optimal aperture (f/5.6-f/11)
• Manual focus
• Lowest ISO
• RAW format

**Focus Sequence:**
1. Start at nearest focus point
2. Take first shot
3. Move focus incrementally
4. Overlap 30-40% between frames
5. Continue to farthest point

**Guidelines:**
• Macro (1:1): 20-50 shots, 1-2mm increments
• Product: 5-15 shots, 5-10mm increments
• Landscape: 3-5 shots, hyperfocal distances

### Post-Processing

**Software Options:**
• Photoshop (auto-stack layers)
• Helicon Focus (specialized)
• Zerene Stacker (macro standard)

**Workflow:**
1. Import image sequence
2. Auto-align frames
3. Blend stacked images
4. Refine and remove artifacts
5. Final adjustments

### Common Issues
**Halos:** Reduce blend radius, manual masking
**Ghosting:** Subject moved, use clone tool
**Poor alignment:** Reshoot with better stability

### Applications
• E-commerce products
• Jewelry photography
• Macro nature photography
• Landscape foreground-to-background
• Architectural detail work

Focus stacking is essential for commercial work requiring exceptional sharpness throughout the frame.""",
