      "content": """# HDR Photography

## High Dynamic Range Explained

HDR combines multiple exposures to capture scenes with brightness range exceeding single-shot capability.

### When to Use HDR
• High-contrast landscapes (bright sky, dark foreground)
• Interior/exterior combinations (real estate)
• Architectural photography
• Any scene exceeding camera dynamic range

**Don't use HDR:**
• Moving subjects (creates ghosting)
• When single exposure suffices
• Fast-changing light conditions

### HDR Capture Technique

**Camera Setup:**
• Tripod required (critical)
• Manual mode
• Aperture priority acceptable
• Auto-bracketing feature
• RAW format

**Bracket Settings:**
• Standard: 3 shots (-2, 0, +2 EV)
• High contrast: 5 shots (-4, -2, 0, +2, +4)
• Extreme: 7-9 shots

**Shooting Process:**
1. Compose and lock tripod
2. Set base exposure
3. Enable bracketing
4. Use burst mode or timer
5. Shoot complete sequence

### Natural HDR Processing

**The Goal:** Realistic enhancement, not over-processed look

**Software Options:**
• Lightroom (Photo Merge HDR)
• Photomatix Pro (industry standard)
• Aurora HDR (user-friendly)
• Photoshop (Merge to HDR Pro)

**Processing Steps:**

1. **Import Bracket**
   • Load exposure sequence
   • Ensure alignment
   • Check for movement

2. **Initial Merge**
   • Auto-align images
   • De-ghost moving elements
   • Generate 32-bit HDR

3. **Tone Mapping**
   • Compress dynamic range
   • Maintain natural look
   • Avoid halos and artifacts

4. **Refinement**
   • Recover highlights
   • Lift shadows naturally
   • Enhance local contrast
   • Control color saturation

### Avoiding HDR Mistakes

**Common Pitfalls:**

❌ **Over-processed look**
• Too much structure/clarity
• Unnatural halos
• Over-saturated colors
**Fix:** Reduce strength, subtle adjustments

❌ **Ghosting artifacts**
• Moving subjects (people, cars, trees)
• Clouds in different positions
**Fix:** Use deghosting, manual masking

❌ **Poor alignment**
• Camera movement between shots
• Hand-held shooting
**Fix:** Always use tripod, reshoot

❌ **Flat, lifeless images**
• Over-compression of tones
• Loss of contrast
**Fix:** Maintain some contrast, targeted adjustments

### Natural HDR Principles

**Keep it Subtle:**
• HDR should be invisible
• Viewer shouldn't detect processing
• Enhance, don't transform

**Targeted Adjustments:**
• Use graduated filters digitally
• Adjust sky and foreground separately
• Maintain natural light direction

**Contrast Management:**
• Don't flatten all tones
• Preserve shadows where appropriate
• Keep highlights interesting

### Real Estate HDR

**Specific Technique:**
• 3-bracket standard (-2, 0, +2)
• Interior/exterior balance
• Natural window light
• Warm, inviting tone

**Client Expectations:**
• Bright, open spaces
• Visible detail everywhere
• Natural color temperature
• Minimal artifacts

### Landscape HDR

**Best Practices:**
• Shoot during golden hour
• 3-5 brackets usually sufficient
• Watch for cloud movement
• Enhance natural drama

**Processing Goals:**
• Rich, detailed shadows
• Textured clouds
• Natural color saturation
• Maintained depth

### Architectural HDR

**Considerations:**
• Straight lines (avoid halos)
• Texture preservation
• Natural material appearance
• Balance interior/exterior

### Alternative: Single-RAW HDR

Modern cameras have excellent dynamic range. Sometimes "HDR" processing on single RAW works:

**When to Use:**
• Static scenes, no time for brackets
• Moving elements present
• Quick workflow needed

**Technique:**
• Expose to the right (ETTR)
• Push shadows in post
• Pull highlights as needed
• Less dynamic range than true HDR

### HDR for Different Genres

**Real Estate:** Clean, bright, inviting
**Landscape:** Dramatic but natural
**Architecture:** Detailed, balanced
**Interior:** Well-lit, color-accurate

### Workflow Efficiency

**Time Investment:**
• Shooting: 2-3 minutes per scene
• Processing: 5-15 minutes per HDR
• Batch processing available

**File Management:**
• Keep brackets organized
• Name HDRs clearly
• Archive original brackets

HDR done right enhances dynamic range naturally, providing commercial-quality results for challenging lighting situations.""",
