      "content": """# Advanced Portrait Lighting

## Professional Portrait Lighting

Advanced portrait lighting creates mood, flatters subjects, and achieves commercial-quality results for beauty, fashion, and editorial photography.

### Beauty Lighting

**Clamshell Lighting:**
• Key light above, angled down
• Reflector or fill below
• Creates even, flattering light
• Minimizes shadows under eyes

**Setup:**
• Large softbox or beauty dish above
• White reflector below eye level
• Subject close to lights
• Shoot between lights

**Best For:**
• Beauty and cosmetics
• Headshots and close-ups
• Flawless skin appearance

### Fashion Lighting

**Dramatic Edge Lighting:**
• Rim lights from behind/sides
• Creates outline, separation
• Dark background emphasis
• Editorial, artistic look

**High-Contrast Fashion:**
• Single hard light source
• Deep shadows, defined features
• Dramatic makeup emphasis
• Bold, striking images

### Advanced Techniques

**Feathering Light:**
• Aim light past subject
• Use edge of light, not center
• Softer, more controlled
• Professional subtlety

**Subtractive Lighting:**
• Use black flags to block light
• Create shadows intentionally
• Sculpt light precisely
• Professional studio technique

**Light Painting:**
• Move light during long exposure
• Create custom lighting patterns
• Artistic, controlled results
• Studio or location

### Skin Tone Control

**Lighting for Different Skin Tones:**
• Lighter skin: Lower contrast, soft light
• Medium skin: Flexible, most forgiving
• Darker skin: Higher power, rim lighting crucial

**Common Issues:**
• Hot spots on oily skin (powder, diffusion)
• Under-eye shadows (fill light, reflector)
• Uneven skin tone (proper white balance, gels)

### Hair Lighting

**Hair/Rim Light:**
• Behind and above subject
• Separates from background
• Creates dimension and shine
• 1-2 stops brighter than key

**Position:**
• 45° behind subject
• High enough to clear face
• Aimed at hair crown
• Grid or snoot for control

### Catchlights

**The Eyes' Reflection:**
• Shows light position/size
• Brings life to eyes
• Larger = softer light source
• Position matters (aesthetic)

**Ideal Catchlight:**
• 10-11 o'clock or 1-2 o'clock position
• Bright but not blown out
• Natural-looking size
• Consider eyeglasses reflections

### Group Portrait Lighting

**Challenges:**
• Even light across all subjects
• Depth positioning
• Individual adjustments

**Solutions:**
• Large, distant light source
• Multiple lights for coverage
• Even spacing of subjects
• Test exposure on different positions

### Environmental Portraits

**On-Location Lighting:**
• Balance ambient + artificial
• Portable lighting solutions
• Quick setup requirements
• Weather considerations

**Techniques:**
• Off-camera flash for direction
• High-speed sync for shallow DOF
• Reflectors for fill
• Natural light modification

### Professional Workflow

**Pre-Shoot:**
1. Discuss look with client/subject
2. Plan lighting setup
3. Test lights before subject arrives
4. Prepare backup equipment

**During Shoot:**
1. Start with key light only
2. Add fill and effects incrementally
3. Check every light position
4. Monitor highlights and shadows

**Post-Shoot:**
1. Tether review if possible
2. Quick select best shots
3. Note lighting setup for future
4. Backup immediately

### Retouching Integration

**Lighting for Easier Retouching:**
• Even skin lighting reduces work
• Proper fill avoids heavy shadow recovery
• Clean background separation
• Controlled highlights preserve detail

**Common Retouching:**
• Skin smoothing (frequency separation)
• Blemish removal
• Eye enhancement
• Hair flyaways

### Professional Portrait Genres

**Headshots:**
• Approachable, friendly light
• Even, flattering
• Sharp focus on eyes
• Neutral or simple background

**Beauty:**
• Perfect skin rendering
• Careful highlight control
• Flattering angles
• Makeup and styling emphasis

**Fashion Editorial:**
• Creative, artistic lighting
• Mood and concept driven
• Bold choices accepted
• Story-telling through light

### Lighting Mood Guide

**High-Key (Bright, Airy):**
• White background, overexposed
• Soft, wrapped light
• Minimal shadows
• Lifestyle, family, beauty

**Low-Key (Dark, Dramatic):**
• Black background
• Single dramatic light
• Deep shadows
• Editorial, artistic, masculine

**Natural/Lifestyle:**
• Mimics window light
• Soft, directional
• Organic feel
• Real-world applications

### Equipment Recommendations

**Essential:**
• 2-3 strobes or continuous lights
• Large softbox (3-4 feet)
• Beauty dish
• Reflectors (various colors)
• Light meter

**Advanced:**
• Hair light with grid
• Background lights
• Colored gels
• Scrims and flags
• Quality light stands

Professional portrait lighting transforms average photos into commercial-quality images that flatter subjects and meet client expectations.""",
