      "subtitle": "Mastering portable artificial light",
      "description": "Learn to use speedlights effectively on and off-camera. Master bounce flash, modifiers, and balancing flash with ambient light.",
      "content": """# Speedlight Mastery

## Portable Power

Speedlights are versatile tools that can transform your photography when used correctly. Move beyond the "deer in headlights" look to professional lighting.

### On-Camera Techniques

**Bounce Flash:**
• Never point flash directly at subject
• Bounce off white ceilings or walls
• Creates large, soft light source
• Use the "black foamie thing" to flag direct light

**Fill Flash:**
• Use outdoors in bright sun
• Fills harsh shadows
• Balances subject with background
• TTL mode usually works well here

### Off-Camera Flash (OCF)

**Getting the Flash Off Camera:**
• Requires trigger/receiver system
• Allows directional lighting control
• Creates depth and dimension
• The key to professional results

**Key Positions:**
• 45 degrees (Rembrandt)
• 90 degrees (Split)
• Backlight (Rim/Hair)

### Balancing with Ambient

**The Two-Exposure Method:**
1. Expose for the background (shutter speed/ISO)
2. Expose for the subject (flash power/aperture)
3. Sync speed limit (usually 1/200s)

**High Speed Sync (HSS):**
• Allows shutter speeds faster than 1/200s
• Crushes ambient light
• Uses more battery power
• Essential for wide aperture outdoors

### Modifiers for Speedlights

• **Softbox:** Softens shadows
• **Umbrella:** Broad, soft spread
• **Grid:** Focuses beam, prevents spill
• **Gels:** Color correction or creative effect

Mastering your speedlight gives you the power to create great light anywhere, anytime.""",
